text=:Category: PracticeCategory%0a:Title: Is Shakespeare Even English?%0a:Author: aryans%0a:Section: B%0a:Completed: 01.02.2021 - 16:13%0a:Status: ungraded%0a%0a%0a#foxbegin 210205-173052-699190#%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a#foxend 210205-173052-699190#%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow much does a language have to change to not be considered the same language anymore?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aAs a high school student in the United States, I had to read my fair share of Shakespeare. We used editions which gave the original Shakespeare on the right page and the translation into plain English on the opposing left page. I also took Mandarin Chinese in high school, and I noticed that the organizational structure in the Shakespeare editions was extremely similar to that of passages in my Chinese textbook. That’s when I began to think that something was fishy about this Shakespeare business. If I had to translate it into English to understand it, it wasn’t English, was it? %0aI already had a rudimentary understanding of the fact that languages change over time, and that this effect compounded over centuries can have drastic consequences. For example, Old English, the earliest form of English spoken in the latter half of the first millennium, is completely unintelligible to any ordinary speaker of modern English. Beowulf is an epic poem originally written in Old English, and all that usually sells is the modern translation without the Old English original. Here’s a block of the first three lines of the original Old English Beowulf from Poetry Foundation for reference:%0aHwæt. We Gardena in geardagum, %0aþeodcyninga, þrym gefrunon, %0ahu ða æþelingas ellen fremedon. %0a%0aYeah, I got nothing from that too. I think that most people would agree that Old English is an entirely different language than the English you and I are familiar with, even if your English and my English are slightly different from each other.%0aIn the same vein, there are also significant differences between the English Shakespeare used and the English we use. In fact, translations of Shakespeare into modern speech are often necessary to teach the plays effectively. I would say that this means that the language Shakespeare wrote in is not the same language that we call English. Thus formed the crux of my argument to my AP literature teacher that it was inappropriate to teach Shakespeare in a class on English literature. %0aI was, of course, joking (although I did want to get out of reading Shakespeare). But I always wondered where the line was. At what point has a language changed so much that it’s no longer the same language? %0aResources: %0aBeowulf (Old English Version). Poetry Foundation, retrieved 1 Feb 2021, from%0a	https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/43521/beowulf-old-english-version %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----
